1.2 Note that yeastProt[,4], returns the 4th column. When we do an operation on it, namely > 500, we apply it to each item in that column, and thus return that column in which each object was applie under that operation, and thus we get a column of logical classes. Then, when we input that into yeasProt, we are giving a true or false value for each row, and asking for the object on the third column. Then, only the rows in which their length was greater than 500 would be true and thus will return its abundance

2.8 (a) Compare the top 5 differentially expressed genes to those that were used as the predictive set in Figure 3 of the Golub et al. paper which of these genes is not used in the set of predictors? 1. Cystatin C, IL-8 Precursor, IL-8, and Adipsin are all found in the predictive set in Figure 3, while MPO Myeloperoxidase is not.

2.8 (b) Why might a ranking based solely on differences in mean expression be an inadequate metric for determining the best predictors of cancer subtype? Suppose that ALL affects the expression of A and B, while AML affects the expression of C and D. B and C are gene expression we commonly associate with Leukemeia (i.e, B is the gene expression that is associated with the affects of blood cancer in white blood cells, and C is the gene expression that is associated with the affects of blood cancer on red blood cells). In the case that we happen ot come across B and C gene expressions, we deduce that the differences in those mean expression will allow us to predict which cancer subtype it is. However, A (from ALL) and D (from AML), might not necessarily be related to why we observe the phenotype in Leukemia, and thus we can imagine a world in which a difference in the mean expression of A and D will not allow us to predict whether the the gene expression is caused from ALL or AML.

2.8 (c) What might be a better statistical metric for identifying genes to become part of the predictive set? (If you are stuck, feel free to browse the Golub et al. paper to see what they actually did, though this is not necessarily the only correct answer.) Reading Golub et al, first column of page 533 gives more insight what particular genes become good predictors. They were usually highly instructive in the sense that those genes exhibits particular phenotypes that we know to be part of ALL/AML. This is different than just two genes that have a high mean difference in expression, because it has the added condition that we know these genes to also exhibit itself differently in the two cancer subtypes

3.10 There are two density plots, one for ALL patients and AML patients. To understand this plot, suppose that we want to know how likely it is for an ALL patient (green) to have normalized cyclin D3 expression between 1.5 and 2.5. Since this is a density plot, we can take the area under the curve between 1.5 and 2.5, which will tell us which percent of the ALL patients can likely be found between those ranges. Basically, the graph is telling us a distribution of how common it is for ALL and AML patients to have certain D3 expressions, and thus taking the area under a range will tell us how likely it is for an ALL or AML patient to be between those ranges.

# count the num of Pyrimdines (T's plus C's)
frequencyPyrimidine <- function(seq) {
  counts <- table(seq)
  num_T <- counts[["t"]]
  num_C <- counts[["c"]]
  
  return(num_T + num_C)

}
# count the num of Purines (A's plus G's)
frequencyPurine <- function(seq) {
  counts <- table(seq)
  num_A <- counts[["a"]]
  num_G <- counts[["g"]]
  
  return(num_A + num_G)
}

frequencyPurine(covid_seq)
## [1] 14817
frequencyPyrimidine(covid_seq)
## [1] 15086

4.7a The weight of RNA and DNA nucleotides are different because RNA has the addition of another hydroxyl group on the 2nd carbon of the pentose. This is also why RNA are more unstable because of the polarity located on the 2nd carbon.

4.7b

# these weights are in the sequence of ATCG or AUCG respectively:
# 29.2, 306.2, 305.2, and 345.2
DNA_weights = c(313.2, 304.2, 289.2, 329.2)
RNA_weights = c(329.2, 306.2, 305.2, 345.2)

seqWeight <- function(seq, type="DNA") {
  if (type == "DNA") {
    seq.fac <- factor(seq, levels=c("a", "t", "c", "g"), labels=DNA_weights)
  } else if (type == "RNA") {
    seq.fac <- factor(seq, levels=c("a", "u", "c", "g"), labels=RNA_weights)
  } else {
    stop("invalid type")
  }
  
  seq.fac
}

get_comp_nucleotide <- function(nucleotide) {
  if (nucleotide == "a") {
    return("t")
  } else if (nucleotide == "t") {
    return("a")
  } else if (nucleotide == "c") {
    return("g")
  } else if (nucleotide == "g") {
    return("c")
  } else {
    stop("invalid nucleotide")
  }
}

compStrand <- function(strand) {
  comp_strand <- map_chr(rev(strand), get_comp_nucleotide)
  return(comp_strand)
}

compStrand(seq)
##  [1] "t" "a" "t" "c" "t" "c" "c" "g" "a" "a" "t" "a" "t" "c"

GC_Content <- function (seq) {
  len <- length(seq)
  return(sum(seq == "g" | seq == "c") / len)
}

windowStartPositions <- function(seq_len, window_size, step_size) {
  start_positions <- c()
  start <- 1
  while (start + window_size - 1 <= seq_len) {
    start_positions <- append(start_positions, start)
    start <- start + step_size
  }
  
  return(start_positions)
}

windowStartPositions(length(covid_seq), 4000, 4000)

4.11

sliding_GC <- function(seq, window_size, step_size) {
  GC_contents <- c()
  
  seq_len <- length(seq)
  window_positions <- windowStartPositions(seq_len, window_size, step_size)
  
  for (window_start in window_positions) {
    window_end <- window_start + step_size - 1
    GC_contents <- append(GC_contents, GC_Content(seq[window_start:window_end]))
  }
  
  return(GC_contents)
}

sliding_GC(covid_seq, 4000, 4000)
## [1] 0.40475 0.35450 0.36775 0.38375 0.37950 0.35600 0.38550

4.12

plotSlidingGC <- function(seq, window_size, step_size) {
  seq_len <- length(seq)
  
  window_positions <- windowStartPositions(seq_len, window_size, step_size)
  GC_contents <- sliding_GC(seq, window_size, step_size)
  
  plot(x=window_positions, y=GC_contents, pch = '.', type = "o", main=sprintf("plotted with Window Size %d and Step Size %d", window_size, step_size))
}

plotSlidingGC(covid_seq, 4000, 4000)

plotSlidingGC(covid_seq, 4000, 1000)

plotSlidingGC(covid_seq, 1000, 1000)

plotSlidingGC(covid_seq, 1000, 100)

plotSlidingGC(covid_seq, 8000, 100)

The window size when increased increases the range in which we calculate the the GC_content for and thus makes the graph seem more averaged out. Decreasing it allows us to focus in on the different regions of the sequence. The step_size simply determines the number of positions we want to look at, increasing it allows us to look at more instances.
